### Awards and honors

A catalog of the various medals and titles humanity felt obligated to give him:

*   **1956** – Elected a [Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS)](/List_of_Fellows_of_the_Royal_Society_elected_in_1956) [1]
*   **1964** – Honorary Member of the [Hungarian Academy of Sciences](/Hungarian_Academy_of_Sciences)
*   **1964** – [D.Sc](/Doctor_of_Science)., [University of London](/University_of_London)
*   **1967** – [Young Medal and Prize](/Young_Medal_and_Prize), for distinguished research in the field of [optics](/Optics)
*   **1967** – Columbus Award of the International Institute for Communications, [Genoa](/Genoa)
*   **1968** – The first [Albert A. Michelson Medal](/Albert_A._Michelson_Medal) from The [Franklin Institute](/Franklin_Institute), [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia) [29]
*   **1968** – [Rumford Medal](/Rumford_Medal) of the Royal Society
*   **1970** – [Honorary Doctorate](/Honorary_Doctorate), [University of Southampton](/University_of_Southampton)
*   **1970** – [Medal of Honor](/IEEE_Medal_of_Honor) of the [Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers](/Institute_of_Electrical_and_Electronics_Engineers)
*   **1970** – Commander of the [Order of the British Empire](/Order_of_the_British_Empire) (CBE)
*   **1971** – [Nobel Prize in Physics](/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics), for his invention and development of the holographic method
*   **1971** – [Honorary Doctorate](/Honorary_Doctorate), [Delft University of Technology](/Delft_University_of_Technology)
*   **1972** – [Holweck Prize](/Fernand_Holweck_Medal_and_Prize) of the Société Française de Physique
*   **1972** – Honorary Member of the Optical Society of America
*   **1983** – The [International Society for Optical Engineering](/International_Society_for_Optical_Engineering) (SPIE) established the annual [Dennis Gabor Award](/Dennis_Gabor_Award), "in recognition of outstanding accomplishments in diffractive wavefront technologies, especially those which further the development of holography and [metrology](/Metrology) applications." [30]
*   **1989** – The [Royal Society of London](/Royal_Society_of_London) began issuing the [Gabor Medal](/Gabor_Medal) for "acknowledged distinction of interdisciplinary work between the life sciences with other disciplines". [31]
*   **1992** – [Gábor Dénes College](/G%C3%A1bor_D%C3%A9nes_College) in [Budapest](/Budapest), [Hungary](/Hungary), is named after him.
*   **1993** – The [NOVOFER Foundation](/NOVOFER_Foundation) of the [Hungarian Academy of Sciences](/Hungarian_Academy_of_Sciences) established its annual [International Dennis Gabor Award](/International_Dennis_Gabor_Award), for outstanding young scientists researching in the fields of physics and applied technology.
*   **2000** – The asteroid [72071 Gábor](/72071_G%C3%A1bor) is named after him.
*   **2008** – The [Institute of Physics](/Institute_of_Physics) renamed its Duddell Medal and Prize, established in 1923, into the [Dennis Gabor Medal and Prize](/Dennis_Gabor_Medal_and_Prize).
*   **2009** – Imperial College London opened the Gabor Hall. [32]
*   Dennis-Gabor-Straße in [Potsdam](/Potsdam) is named in his honour and is the location of the Potsdamer Centrum für Technologie.

### In popular culture

The strange, lingering echoes of a significant life:

*   The [Gabor family](/List_of_Jem_characters) from the animated TV series [Jem and The Holograms](/Jem_(TV_series)) was, rather pointedly, named after Dennis Gabor.
*   On 5 June 2010, the logo for the [Google](/Google) website was temporarily redrawn to resemble a hologram, a nod to what would have been Dennis Gabor's 110th birthday. [33]
*   In [David Foster Wallace](/David_Foster_Wallace)'s sprawling novel [Infinite Jest](/Infinite_Jest), the character Hal suggests that "Dennis Gabor may very well have been the Antichrist." A sentiment that, depending on your view of technology, might not be entirely without merit. [34]